<!--
  rag-explainer.ytml
  ───────────────────
  Topic  : Retrieval-Augmented Generation — teaching LLMs about your own data
  Duration: ~2.8 minutes  |  8 slides
  Demonstrates: typewriter code animation, Mermaid flow diagrams, staggered reveals

  Run from the package/ directory so HTML_ASSETS resolves correctly:
    cd package
    ytml -i samples/rag-explainer.ytml -o rag-explainer.mp4 --use-gtts

  Optional background music:
    Add an MP3 to assets/ and uncomment the global-music tag below.
-->
<ytml>
  <config>
    FRAME_RATE=30
    VIDEO_WIDTH=1920
    VIDEO_HEIGHT=1088
    ENABLE_AI_VOICE=False
    HTML_ASSETS={"animations": ["js/typewriter_effect.js"]}
  </config>

  <!-- <global-music src="assets/lofi-ambient.mp3" start="0s" end="175s" loop="true" /> -->

  <!-- ── Slide 1 : Hook ─────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <segment>
    <frame duration="6s">
      <div style="
        height: 100vh;
        background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0f0a1a 0%, #1a0a2e 60%, #0d0d0d 100%);
        display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center;
        font-family: 'Segoe UI', sans-serif; overflow: hidden;
      ">
        <div style="text-align: center; padding: 40px; max-width: 1000px;">
          <p style="
            color: #8b5cf6; font-size: 1em; letter-spacing: 8px;
            text-transform: uppercase; margin: 0 0 20px;
            animation: fadeUp 0.7s ease-out both;
          ">2025 AI PATTERN</p>
          <h1 style="
            color: #fff; font-size: 4em; font-weight: 900; margin: 0 0 18px;
            line-height: 1.1;
            animation: blurIn 1s 0.2s ease-out both;
          ">Retrieval-Augmented<br/>Generation</h1>
          <p style="
            color: #a78bfa; font-size: 1.5em; margin: 0;
            animation: slideUpFade 0.9s 0.6s ease-out both;
          ">Teaching LLMs about your data — without retraining</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <style>
        @keyframes blurIn {
          from { opacity: 0; filter: blur(14px); transform: scale(1.06); }
          to   { opacity: 1; filter: blur(0px); transform: scale(1); }
        }
        @keyframes slideUpFade {
          from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(30px); }
          to   { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); }
        }
      </style>
    </frame>
    <voice start="0.5s" end="5.5s">
      What if your LLM could answer questions about your documents, your database, or
      yesterday's news — without any fine-tuning? That's what RAG solves.
    </voice>
  </segment>

  <transition type="fade" duration="0.5s" />

  <!-- ── Slide 2 : The problem ─────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <segment>
    <frame duration="20s">
      <div style="
        height: 100vh; background: #0d0d0d;
        display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center;
        font-family: 'Segoe UI', sans-serif; padding: 60px;
      ">
        <div style="max-width: 900px; width: 100%;">
          <h2 style="
            color: #f87171; font-size: 2.4em; margin: 0 0 40px;
            animation: fadeUp 0.7s ease-out both;
          ">Why LLMs fail at real-world questions</h2>
          <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 24px;">
            <div style="
              display: flex; align-items: flex-start; gap: 20px;
              animation: slideInLeft 0.7s 0.3s ease-out both;
            ">
              <span style="font-size: 1.8em; min-width: 44px;">⏰</span>
              <div>
                <p style="color: #fff; font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 4px; font-weight: 600;">Knowledge cutoff</p>
                <p style="color: #888; font-size: 1.05em; margin: 0;">Training data is frozen — the model knows nothing after its cutoff date.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div style="
              display: flex; align-items: flex-start; gap: 20px;
              animation: slideInLeft 0.7s 0.6s ease-out both;
            ">
              <span style="font-size: 1.8em; min-width: 44px;">🔒</span>
              <div>
                <p style="color: #fff; font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 4px; font-weight: 600;">Private data is invisible</p>
                <p style="color: #888; font-size: 1.05em; margin: 0;">Your internal docs, databases, and wikis were never in the training set.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div style="
              display: flex; align-items: flex-start; gap: 20px;
              animation: fadeUp 0.7s 0.9s ease-out both;
            ">
              <span style="font-size: 1.8em; min-width: 44px;">🎭</span>
              <div>
                <p style="color: #fff; font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 4px; font-weight: 600;">Confident hallucinations</p>
                <p style="color: #888; font-size: 1.05em; margin: 0;">When the model doesn't know, it fabricates — fluently and convincingly.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <style>
        @keyframes fadeUp {
          from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(18px); }
          to   { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); }
        }
      </style>
    </frame>
    <voice start="0.5s" end="19s">
      LLMs have three fundamental gaps: their knowledge is frozen at training time,
      they can't see your private data, and when they don't know something,
      they often invent a plausible-sounding answer. RAG fixes all three.
    </voice>
  </segment>

  <transition type="fade" duration="0.5s" />

  <!-- ── Slide 3 : What is RAG — Mermaid overview ──────────────────── -->
  <segment>
    <frame duration="22s" static="true">
      <div style="
        height: 100vh; background: #0d0d0d;
        display: flex; flex-direction: column;
        align-items: center; justify-content: center;
        font-family: 'Segoe UI', sans-serif; padding: 40px;
      ">
        <h2 style="color: #8b5cf6; font-size: 2em; margin: 0 0 32px;">How RAG works</h2>
        <mermaid>
          flowchart LR
            A["📄 Your Documents"] --> B["Chunk + Embed"]
            B --> C[("🗄️ Vector DB")]

            D["❓ User Query"] --> E["Embed Query"]
            E --> F["Similarity Search"]
            F --> C
            C --> G["Top-K Chunks"]

            G --> H["Build Prompt"]
            D --> H
            H --> I["🤖 LLM"]
            I --> J["✅ Grounded Answer"]

            style A fill:#1e1b4b,color:#a78bfa
            style C fill:#1e1b4b,color:#a78bfa
            style I fill:#1e1b4b,color:#a78bfa
            style J fill:#14532d,color:#86efac
        </mermaid>
      </div>
    </frame>
    <voice start="0.5s" end="21s">
      RAG has two phases. Offline: your documents are chunked, embedded into vectors,
      and stored in a vector database. Online: when a query arrives, it's embedded too,
      the most similar chunks are retrieved, and those chunks are passed as context to the LLM —
      giving it exactly the information it needs to answer accurately.
    </voice>
  </segment>

  <transition type="fade" duration="0.5s" />

  <!-- ── Slide 4 : Step 1 — Index ──────────────────────────────────── -->
  <segment>
    <frame duration="28s">
      <div style="
        height: 100vh; background: #0d0d0d;
        display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center;
        font-family: 'Segoe UI', sans-serif; padding: 60px;
      ">
        <div style="max-width: 1100px; width: 100%;">
          <div style="
            display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 16px; margin-bottom: 28px;
            animation: fadeIn 0.6s ease-out both;
          ">
            <span style="
              background: #8b5cf6; color: #fff; font-size: 0.9em;
              font-weight: 700; padding: 4px 14px; border-radius: 20px;
              letter-spacing: 2px; text-transform: uppercase;
            ">STEP 1</span>
            <h2 style="color: #fff; font-size: 1.8em; margin: 0;">Index your documents</h2>
          </div>
          <pre><code class="language-python">
from openai import OpenAI
import chromadb

client = OpenAI()
col    = chromadb.Client().create_collection("knowledge")

def index(text: str, doc_id: str) -> None:
    vec = client.embeddings.create(
        model="text-embedding-3-small",
        input=text
    ).data[0].embedding

    col.add(
        ids=[doc_id],
        embeddings=[vec],
        documents=[text]
    )

# Index every document once — offline step
index("Our refund policy is 30 days...", "doc-001")
          </code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
      <style>
        @keyframes fadeIn {
          from { opacity: 0; }
          to   { opacity: 1; }
        }
        pre { background: #1a1a2e; border-radius: 10px; padding: 28px; margin: 0; }
        pre code { font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.7; }
      </style>
    </frame>
    <voice start="0.5s" end="27s">
      Step one: indexing. Pass each document through an embedding model — this converts
      text into a dense vector that captures its meaning. Store the vectors in a vector database
      like ChromaDB, Pinecone, or pgvector. This is a one-time offline process.
      Every chunk gets a numeric fingerprint based on its semantic content.
    </voice>
  </segment>

  <transition type="fade" duration="0.5s" />

  <!-- ── Slide 5 : Step 2 — Retrieve ───────────────────────────────── -->
  <segment>
    <frame duration="26s">
      <div style="
        height: 100vh; background: #0d0d0d;
        display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center;
        font-family: 'Segoe UI', sans-serif; padding: 60px;
      ">
        <div style="max-width: 1100px; width: 100%;">
          <div style="
            display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 16px; margin-bottom: 28px;
            animation: fadeIn 0.6s ease-out both;
          ">
            <span style="
              background: #06b6d4; color: #000; font-size: 0.9em;
              font-weight: 700; padding: 4px 14px; border-radius: 20px;
              letter-spacing: 2px; text-transform: uppercase;
            ">STEP 2</span>
            <h2 style="color: #fff; font-size: 1.8em; margin: 0;">Retrieve relevant chunks</h2>
          </div>
          <pre><code class="language-python">
def retrieve(query: str, top_k: int = 3) -> list[str]:
    # Embed the query with the same model used at index time
    vec = client.embeddings.create(
        model="text-embedding-3-small",
        input=query
    ).data[0].embedding

    # Semantic nearest-neighbour search
    hits = col.query(
        query_embeddings=[vec],
        n_results=top_k
    )
    return hits["documents"][0]  # list of matching text chunks
          </code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
      <style>
        @keyframes fadeIn {
          from { opacity: 0; }
          to   { opacity: 1; }
        }
        pre { background: #0a1929; border-radius: 10px; padding: 28px; margin: 0; }
        pre code { font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.7; }
      </style>
    </frame>
    <voice start="0.5s" end="25s">
      Step two: retrieval. Embed the user's question with the same model you used
      during indexing. Then query the vector database — it returns the chunks whose
      vectors are most similar. This is semantic search: it finds meaning,
      not just matching keywords.
    </voice>
  </segment>

  <transition type="fade" duration="0.5s" />

  <!-- ── Slide 6 : Step 3 — Generate ───────────────────────────────── -->
  <segment>
    <frame duration="26s">
      <div style="
        height: 100vh; background: #0d0d0d;
        display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center;
        font-family: 'Segoe UI', sans-serif; padding: 60px;
      ">
        <div style="max-width: 1100px; width: 100%;">
          <div style="
            display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 16px; margin-bottom: 28px;
            animation: fadeIn 0.6s ease-out both;
          ">
            <span style="
              background: #4ade80; color: #000; font-size: 0.9em;
              font-weight: 700; padding: 4px 14px; border-radius: 20px;
              letter-spacing: 2px; text-transform: uppercase;
            ">STEP 3</span>
            <h2 style="color: #fff; font-size: 1.8em; margin: 0;">Generate a grounded answer</h2>
          </div>
          <pre><code class="language-python">
def rag(question: str) -> str:
    context = "\n---\n".join(retrieve(question))

    response = client.chat.completions.create(
        model="gpt-4o",
        messages=[
            {
                "role": "system",
                "content": f"Answer using only this context:\n\n{context}"
            },
            {"role": "user", "content": question}
        ]
    )
    return response.choices[0].message.content

answer = rag("What is your refund policy?")
          </code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
      <style>
        @keyframes fadeIn {
          from { opacity: 0; }
          to   { opacity: 1; }
        }
        pre { background: #0a1a0f; border-radius: 10px; padding: 28px; margin: 0; }
        pre code { font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.7; }
      </style>
    </frame>
    <voice start="0.5s" end="25s">
      Step three: generation. Bundle the retrieved chunks into a system prompt as context.
      The LLM now has the exact information it needs to answer the question accurately.
      No hallucination — because it's not guessing. It's reading.
    </voice>
  </segment>

  <transition type="fade" duration="0.5s" />

  <!-- ── Slide 7 : Key takeaways ───────────────────────────────────── -->
  <segment>
    <frame duration="20s">
      <div style="
        height: 100vh;
        background: linear-gradient(135deg, #0f0a1a, #1a0a2e);
        display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center;
        font-family: 'Segoe UI', sans-serif; padding: 60px;
      ">
        <div style="max-width: 900px; width: 100%;">
          <h2 style="color: #a78bfa; font-size: 2.4em; margin: 0 0 40px; animation: fadeUp 0.7s ease-out both;">
            Why RAG is the go-to pattern
          </h2>
          <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 24px;">
            <div style="background: rgba(139,92,246,0.1); border: 1px solid rgba(139,92,246,0.3); border-radius: 12px; padding: 24px; animation: fadeUp 0.7s 0.2s ease-out both;">
              <p style="color: #a78bfa; font-size: 1.1em; font-weight: 700; margin: 0 0 8px;">No retraining</p>
              <p style="color: #ccc; font-size: 1em; margin: 0; line-height: 1.5;">Update your docs and the model's knowledge updates instantly.</p>
            </div>
            <div style="background: rgba(6,182,212,0.1); border: 1px solid rgba(6,182,212,0.3); border-radius: 12px; padding: 24px; animation: fadeUp 0.7s 0.4s ease-out both;">
              <p style="color: #06b6d4; font-size: 1.1em; font-weight: 700; margin: 0 0 8px;">Data stays private</p>
              <p style="color: #ccc; font-size: 1em; margin: 0; line-height: 1.5;">Documents never leave your infrastructure — only relevant chunks are sent.</p>
            </div>
            <div style="background: rgba(74,222,128,0.1); border: 1px solid rgba(74,222,128,0.3); border-radius: 12px; padding: 24px; animation: fadeUp 0.7s 0.6s ease-out both;">
              <p style="color: #4ade80; font-size: 1.1em; font-weight: 700; margin: 0 0 8px;">Any LLM, any data</p>
              <p style="color: #ccc; font-size: 1em; margin: 0; line-height: 1.5;">Works with GPT, Claude, Llama — and PDFs, databases, wikis, APIs.</p>
            </div>
            <div style="background: rgba(251,191,36,0.1); border: 1px solid rgba(251,191,36,0.3); border-radius: 12px; padding: 24px; animation: fadeUp 0.7s 0.8s ease-out both;">
              <p style="color: #fbbf24; font-size: 1.1em; font-weight: 700; margin: 0 0 8px;">Citable answers</p>
              <p style="color: #ccc; font-size: 1em; margin: 0; line-height: 1.5;">Return source chunks alongside the answer — full transparency.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <style>
        @keyframes fadeUp {
          from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(16px); }
          to   { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); }
        }
      </style>
    </frame>
    <voice start="0.5s" end="19s">
      RAG is now the backbone of most production AI assistants. No GPU needed,
      your data stays private, it works with any LLM, and answers can link back
      to their source documents. It's the fastest path from raw text to a working AI assistant.
    </voice>
  </segment>

  <transition type="fade" duration="0.5s" />

  <!-- ── Slide 8 : Outro ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <segment>
    <frame duration="18s">
      <div style="
        height: 100vh;
        background: #0d0d0d;
        display: flex; flex-direction: column;
        align-items: center; justify-content: center;
